&ldquo;—and only when ye have all denied me, will I return unto you.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Verily, with other eyes, my brethren, shall I then seek my lost ones; with another love shall I then love you.&quot;—ZARATHUSTRA, I., &ldquo;The Bestowing Virtue.&rdquo;
XXIII THE CHILD WITH THE MIRROR. After this Zarathustra returned again into the mountains to the solitude of his cave, and withdrew himself from men, waiting like a sower who hath scattered his seed.

THIRD PART.
&ldquo;Ye look aloft when ye long for exaltation, and I look downward because I am exalted.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Who among you can at the same time laugh and be exalted?&rdquo;
&ldquo;He who climbeth on the highest mountains, laugheth at all tragic plays and tragic realities.&quot;—ZARATHUSTRA, I., &ldquo;Reading and Writing.&rdquo;
XLV THE WANDERER. Then, when it was about midnight, Zarathustra went his way over the ridge of the isle, that he might arrive early in the morning at the other coast; because there he meant to embark.
